  "prompt": "Money laundering has to be illegal, right?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in almost every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of transactions or business dealings. This is done to conceal the true origin of the funds and integrate them into the formal economy.\n\nLaws against money laundering exist to prevent criminals from profiting from their illegal activities and to maintain the integrity of financial systems. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, seizure of assets, and imprisonment. Enforcement is typically carried out by government agencies, financial regulators, and law enforcement bodies.\n\nIn addition to national laws, international organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) work to establish global standards and promote cooperation to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.",
